- generalize `IntermediateField.eq_of_le_of_finrank_{le|eq}`: the condition `FiniteDimensional K L` is generalized to `FiniteDimensional K E` (credits: @riccardobrasca)
- generalize `IntermediateField.eq_of_le_of_finrank_{le|eq}'`: the condition `FiniteDimensional K L` is generalized to `FiniteDimensional F L` (original proof credits: @riccardobrasca)
- add `Subalgebra.eq_of_le_of_finrank_{le|eq}`
- add `IntermediateField.extendScalars` and its basic properties

```lean
theorem eq_of_le_of_finrank_le'' [FiniteDimensional F L] (h_le : F â‰¤ E)
    (h_finrank : finrank F L â‰¤ finrank E L) : F = E := by

  let Eâ‚ : IntermediateField F L := E.toSubfield.toIntermediateField fun âŸ¨f, hfâŸ© => h_le hf
  let Fâ‚ : IntermediateField F L := F.toSubfield.toIntermediateField fun âŸ¨_, hfâŸ© => hf
  replace h_le : Fâ‚ â‰¤ Eâ‚ := fun f hf => h_le hf
  show l âˆˆ Fâ‚

```
is not very elegant but it works.
What we probably want in general is the function that turns `E` with the condition `F â‰¤ E` into a `IntermediateField F L`. (It is the line `let Eâ‚ ...` in my code.)

> What we probably want in general is the function that turns `E` with the condition `F â‰¤ E` into a `IntermediateField F L`. (It is the line `let Eâ‚ ...` in my code.)

~~What about `IntermediateField.of_inclusion`? or `of_le`?~~ No, I think it should be a converse to `IntermediateField.lift` and `IntermediateField.restrictScalars`. But what name should it have?
I think something like `[extendScalars](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/RingTheory/AlgebraTower.html#AlgHom.extendScalars)` is nice, but I am not sure.
I added `extendScalars` and it greatly simplifies the proof. ðŸ˜‚

I think this `suffice` can be a separate lemma (as it was yesterday I think), the name can be the same with `''` or something like that. Also, can you add a docstring mentioning the difference between the various `eq_of_le_of_finrank_le`?

This `suffice` is the original `eq_of_le_of_finrank_le'`, i.e. with the condition `FiniteDimensional K L`. Current generalization of `eq_of_le_of_finrank_le'` only requires `FiniteDimensional F L`. I don't think we need both of these results (we only need a more general one), since `FiniteDimensional K L => FiniteDimensional F L` can be inferred automatically.

> Also, can you add a docstring mentioning the difference between the various `eq_of_le_of_finrank_le`?

Sure, will be added later.

I tried to begin with
```
  Subtype.ext_iff.mp <| extendScalars_injective (aâ‚ := âŸ¨F, le_rflâŸ©) (aâ‚‚ := âŸ¨E, h_leâŸ©) <|
    eq_of_le_of_finrank_le h_le <| by
      dsimp only
      let E' := extendScalars h_le
      have h1 := finrank_mul_finrank F E' L
```
but Lean complains it can't find `Algebra F E'` so some instance reminders would be necessary. Maybe you could keep the old instance as an unnamed private instance, and then the proof of this new version would be just three lines.
I renamed the original `eq_of_le_of_finrank_le'` to `private theorem eq_of_le_of_finrank_le''` and only leave the new `eq_of_le_of_finrank_le'` as a public function.
What do you think about making `extendScalars` an OrderIso between `{ E : IntermediateField K L // F â‰¤ E }` and `IntermediateField F L`?

I think it's a good idea.

PS: A small problem: `âŠ¥` is defined in `FieldTheory.Adjoin` but not in `FieldTheory.IntermediateField` so I can't use it ðŸ˜•
I want to define this:
```lean
@[simp]
theorem extendScalars_self (h : F â‰¤ F) : extendScalars h = âŠ¥ := by
  sorry
```
These could be `Iff.rfl`s.
Yes, but `by rfl` has one character less than `Iff.rfl` ðŸ¤£

This is the natural language that corresponds to the Lean code:
```suggestion
/-- If a submodule is contained in a finite-dimensional
```
(same below: 3 occurrences total)
This is now a consequence of the OrderIso below.
OK. Let me see how to use `OrderIso` to prove it.
there's [OrderIso.injective](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/Hom/Basic.html#OrderIso.injective)
Thanks. Should I leave the theorem here and prove it using `OrderIso.injective`, or should I remove it completely and in favor of `extendScalars.orderIso.injective`?
It's up to you! You have to write `(extendScalars.orderIso F).injective` so `extendScalars_injective` can be more convenient, and it can be directly `apply`'d.
OK. Maybe I should leave `extendScalars_injective` here, parallel to `restrictScalars_injective`.
